Iterable of iterables of LinearOperator objects, each with the same dtype. Each element of operators corresponds to a row- partition, in top-to-bottom order. trans-unit.source: Mean Intersection-Over-Union is a common evaluation metric for semantic image segmentation, which first computes the IOU for each semantic class and then computes the average over classes. IOU is defined as follows: IOU = true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive + false_negative). The predictions are accumulated in a confusion matrix, weighted by sample_weight and the metric is then calculated from it.
trans-unit.target: Mean Intersection-Over-Union es una métrica de evaluación común para la segmentación de imágenes semánticas, que primero calcula el IOU para cada clase semántica y luego calcula el promedio de las clases. IOU se define de la siguiente manera: IOU = true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive + false_negative). Las predicciones se acumulan en una matriz de confusión, ponderada por sample_weight y luego se calcula la métrica a partir de ella.

trans-unit.source: MobileNetV2 is a general architecture and can be used for multiple use cases. Depending on the use case, it can use different input layer size and different width factors. This allows different width models to reduce the number of multiply-adds and thereby reduce inference cost on mobile devices.

MobileNetV2 is very similar to the original MobileNet, except that it uses inverted residual blocks with bottlenecking features. It has a drastically lower parameter count than the original MobileNet. MobileNets support any input size greater than 32 x 32, with larger image sizes offering better performance.

MobileNets support any input size greater than 32 x 32, with larger image sizes offering better performance. The number of parameters and number of multiply-adds can be modified by using the alpha parameter, which increases/decreases the number of filters in each layer. By altering the image size and alpha parameter, all 16 models from the paper can be built, with ImageNet weights provided.
MobileNets: Efficient Convolutional Neural Networks for Mobile Vision Applications
